I have a used Norinco hunter type I ak47, has 20" chrome lined barrel, (2)  5rnd mags and (2) 40rnd mags.
It has a tiny rust spot on the piston tube housing, which can be replaced or polished off. The front sight is canted to one side the slightest bit (which is very common with all ak-47's).
This bad boy accepts all ak47 magazines and drums.
They are perfect for making galil clones (which look awesome!) And fetch big money.
The last picture is a Galil clone conversion! (looks awesome right?)
These rifles are extremely rare and were imported in the 90's to get around the ban, hence the stock and missing pistol grip.
The last picture is a stock photo of one that was converted using a tapco trigger and forend.  Very simple conversion!
Just the 40 round magazines are going for $100 dollars each right now, and I have two in this package! I will even throw in a cheap (kind of broken) plastic rifle case!
These rifles are also very accurate compared to a traditional ak-47's. I've seen these rifles sell for as much as $1,500+on gunbroker.
Here's a Norinco hunter shooting a 75rnd drum! http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2uW-U-zhnQw
Not very many of these left out in the wild, so get it while you can, especially with a ban imminent!

Magpul has posted that they will withdraw their facility from Colorado.  These mags will be hard to find in the interim if Magpul leaves CO.

"Although the bill has been amended to exempt manufacturers, Magpul still plans to leave the state if the measure banning high-capacity magazines passes." 
"We can't disappoint our customers nor ignore our convictions. Anyone who votes in favor of this bill votes to drive over 600 jobs out of [Colorado]," the company said in a post on its Facebook page Thursday.

postcontent: 1984 Ruger Redhawk 5.5" revolver chambered in .357 Magnum.  This 6 shooter was built on the .44 frame and is considered a widely sought after collector's item.  I haven't tested the theory, but the manufacturer and experts alike claim that you can shoot any hand load from this weapon without fear of damaging the frame.  The weapon is in excellent shape for it's age and is a tack driving son-of-a-gun!  Adjustable rear and front sights, stainless steel, catalog number KRH-355.  Have original box, paperwork and first owners warranty papers from 1984.
